Today’s class focused on the Java Collections Framework, which is used to store and manage groups of objects dynamically. 
Collections are part of the java.util package and provide ready-made classes and interfaces for efficient data handling. 
The mentor explained that List and Set are important interfaces in the collection framework.

The List interface is used to store ordered elements, and it allows duplicate values. Classes like ArrayList and LinkedList 
implement the List interface. ArrayList stores elements in a dynamic array and provides fast access using index positions. 

LinkedList stores elements using nodes and links, which makes insertion and deletion easier. Elements in a list can be 
accessed using loops or index positions.

The Set interface is used to store unique elements, and it does not allow duplicate values. HashSet is a commonly used 
class that implements the Set interface. It stores elements in an unordered format and automatically ignores duplicate entries.
This is useful when only unique values are required.

The working flow starts by creating a collection object. Elements are added using the add() method. A loop is used to 
access and display elements. If duplicate values are added in a Set, they are ignored automatically. Collections help in 
managing data efficiently and dynamically.

This concept is important because collections are widely used in Java applications for storing and processing data.
